igious discrimination in the work place.  Does it also apply to small, private companies that do not receive any public funds?<br>
<br>
My husband has his own small IT consulting business, with about 50 clients here in town.  His largest client, which accounts for about 20% of his business, is run bun a man I used to work for (at a different company) - a born again Christian.  He mainly hires people from his church. . . but, occasionally, when he can't fill a position with a church member for whatever reason, he'll run an ad and hire whoever.  <br>
<br>
My dh has done work for this guy for years now, since the company was first started.  Over the years of fixing his email, etc., he's seen things like emails from one GM to another with the subject:  &quot;Should we allow non-Christains on the board of directors?&quot;  or, &quot;Don't forget!  Prayer Meeting at lunch time in the conference room!&quot;  None of this affects him, because he's a private consultant, and Bill (the owner) has only ever attempted to witness to him once.<br>
<br>
Recently, though, one of the few non-xian employees began complaining of religious discrimination -- saying (in my opinion, rightfully) that pushing these prayer meetings was inappropriate, because, even if they are not mandatory, it puts him at a professional disadvantage to refuse. A few days after he filed a formal complaint, he was fired.  Another non-xian employee quit, because a promotion that was promised to him went to a church-member who knew nothing about the business and has proven a liability to the company. <br>
<br>
Plus, I guess Bill &quot;recommends&quot; reading material like &quot;Business by the Book,&quot; (as in the &quot;good&quot; book), and holds &quot;family value&quot; meetings which he somehow attempts to tie into his business.<br>
<br>
Like I said, this doesn't affect my husband. . . but I'm curious as to whether or not any of the other non-religious employees might sucessfully litigate the matter<br>
<br>
Any thoughts?<br>
<br>
Jen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 209<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/5/03 1:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=145.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Anyone know anything about Title VII?</span><hr size=1> Obviously I have no idea about the situation in America...but my MIL worked for a fundie, who held prayer meetings three times a day.  She is an atheist and refused to go...but everyone else in the office went, and it did make her feel very awkward (the cynic in me would say that that was the entire point of the exercise...to get her to feel so uncomfortable that she joined in...the prayer meetings were only started after she told her boss she wasn't interested in his thoughts on religion because she was an atheist! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
Anyway...here there isn't anything you can do about that kind of thing, as far as I know...if they were discriminating against a muslim, or a mormon or someone then that would be different....but (at least here), a prayer meeting isn't discrimination as such. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=minusrusty>minusRusty</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/5/03 1:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=145.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   If I recall correctly, ...</span><hr size=1> ...there is a minimum company size that applies. Something like 15 employees or fewer don't fall under anti-discrimination litigation.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure what the business requirements are, but if the company in any way crosses state boundries to do business or accepts federal money, then the probability that they have to follow Federal Regs greatly increases.<br>
<br>
Not much help, I'm afraid. I'd contact the ACLU or a lawyer.<br>
<br>
-Rusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ctrlaltdelirious>CtrlAltDelirious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/5/03 2:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=145.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Some info</span><hr size=1> According to Title VII <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.eeoc.gov/laws/vii.html">www.eeoc.gov/laws/vii.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>(b) The term ``employer'' means a person engaged in an industry affecting<br>
commerce who has fifteen or more employees for each working day in each of<br>
twenty or more calendar weeks in the current or preceding calendar year,<br>
and any agent of such a person, but such term does not include (1) the<br>
United States, a corporation wholly owned by the Government of the United<br>
States, an Indian tribe, or any department or agency of the District of<br>
Columbia subject by statute to procedures of the competitive service (as<br>
defined in section 2102 of title 5 [of the United States Code]), or<br>
(2) a bona fide private membership club (other than a labor organization)<br>
which is exempt from taxation under section 501(c) of title 26 [the<br>
Internal Revenue Code of 1954], except that during the first year<br>
after March 24, 1972 [the date of enactment of the Equal Employment<br>
Opportunity Act of 1972], persons having fewer than twenty­five<br>
employees (and their agents) shall not be considered employers.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
So if there are more than 25 employees - the owner is an employer under the Act.  Unless he does business across state lines then it falls under (b) above.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>(g) The term ``commerce'' means trade, traffic, commerce,<br>
transportation, transmission, or communication among the several States;<br>
or between a State and any place outside thereof; or within the District<br>
of Columbia, or a possession of the United States; or between points in<br>
the same State but through a point outside thereof.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
