<br>
There are lots of religous descrimination cases, but they tend to follow a 'protected class' standard and unfortunately, atheists are not a protected class.  (Like a racism case filed by a caucasian would find little support in the law because they are not a protected class.)  If any were women or minorities they enjoy a greater degree of protection.  Now, aside from the religion, there are grounds for action based on wrongful termination, and harassment in an opressive workplace, and this environment may qualify.  To survive initial trial motions (to dismiss or strike) there must be a prima facia showing of a pattern of behavior and intent on the employers part (or agents thereof.)<br>
<br>
Let me know the state and I can pull some actual cases for you.<br>
<br>
